  "game_explanation": "This three-player bargaining game features private values on red and blue chips, with green chips known to be worth $0.50 to everyone. Buffalo values blue highly ($0.70) and red very little ($0.10). Bear values blue the most ($1.00) and red moderately ($0.60). Goose values both red and blue very little ($0.10 each). This creates clear gains from trade: Bear strongly wants blue, and Buffalo somewhat wants blue more than red; Goose is almost indifferent across red and blue but still likes green. Green acts as a stable currency everyone values equally. Because players only see their own values, they infer others’ valuations from who tries to buy or sell which color and at what ratios. Buffalo is naturally inclined to sell red and possibly green to acquire blue. Bear strongly tries to acquire blue and is relatively reluctant to give it up. Goose, with low values on red and blue but normal value on green, is a natural seller of red/blue in exchange for green, especially if others pay more than $0.10-per-chip effective value. Strategic uncertainty arises because acceptance is simultaneous and multiple acceptances are randomly resolved, so proposers must consider when an offer is attractive to more than one counterparty. Early rounds are likely exploratory, with conservative trades involving green as a safe baseline; by later rounds, the trade history reveals rough preferences (e.g., who repeatedly tries to buy blue), enabling more targeted surplus-enhancing trades. However, the proposers still never know exact private values, so they shade offers in their favor and sometimes get declined when they misjudge how much surplus they are leaving the counterparties. Overall, we should see Buffalo and Bear competing for blue and using green as payment, while Goose opportunistically sells red/blue to gain green with small but positive personal surplus.",
