{
  "game_explanation": "In this three-player chip bargaining game, each player begins with 10 chips of each color (RED, BLUE, GREEN) and privately values them slightly differently, except for GREEN which is common-value at $0.50 for all. RED is worth $1.00 to everyone, but BLUE ranges from $0.40 (otter) to $0.50 (peacock) to $0.70 (cat). Everyone publicly sees that each color is somewhere within a common range, so they know that RED is likely at the high end of the range, GREEN is fixed at $0.50, and BLUE could be more or less valuable depending on the player. The main source of gains from trade comes from BLUE: cat likely values BLUE more than others, otter the least, with peacock in between. All players know only their own exact values, but they infer that others might differ, particularly on BLUE, creating strategic uncertainty about how aggressive or generous to be. Because RED is clearly strong and symmetric, players expect RED to be hard to acquire and unlikely to be traded away cheaply; GREEN is neutral and can serve as a medium of exchange when values are ambiguous. Given three players and random selection when multiple parties accept, proposers have to structure offers that will induce exactly one likely accepter or at least be indifferent about which counterparty they get. The surplus calculator makes it straightforward for each player to see whether each proposed trade is good or bad for them personally at the moment of decision. As a result, accepted trades are almost always individually profitable in value terms, but may be myopic: players might accept small positive gains now even if that hampers better deals later. Otter, having low BLUE value, is naturally inclined to trade away BLUE and hoard RED; cat wants to acquire BLUE and is relatively more willing to give up GREEN or even some RED if the margin is attractive. Peacock is in between and might opportunistically play both sides: sell some BLUE to cat when cat overpays, or pick up BLUE cheaply from otter if possible. Early rounds likely feature exploratory offers that test how aggressively others will trade and whether anyone seems desperate for particular colors. As the game proceeds, some players will accumulate more of their high-value chips, while others may miss out if they hold out for unrealistically favorable trades. The fixed three-round, three-turn structure also pushes some players—especially those who haven’t yet secured a good trade—toward accepting modest, safe gains in later turns rather than risking ending the game with the initial endowment only. Because each player can see the evolving holdings, proposers in later rounds can tailor offers to exploit inventory imbalances (for example, targeting a cat that already has many BLUE chips and might still accept more if not too expensive). Overall, we expect a few small, clearly positive-sum trades, somewhat conservative use of RED (since all know it is highly valuable), and at least one substantial BLUE-for-RED or BLUE-for-GREEN transfer that favors cat in final surplus, while otter monetizes BLUE into safer RED/Green and peacock tries to extract small gains from both sides without overcommitting.",
