    {
      "round": 0,
      "round_explanation": "In the first round, no one has yet seen any behavior from others, so beliefs about others’ valuations are based only on the public ranges and general intuition (e.g., that BLUE may vary and RED is very strong). Players are likely to start with cautious, mildly favorable offers that test demand and reveal little information. Otter, moving first, is especially uncertain and may try to structure a trade that offloads some low-valued BLUE or neutral GREEN in exchange for more RED, but at terms that are still positive for whoever accepts. Peacock, moving second, will have the benefit of observing otter’s opening move and can pitch a somewhat more targeted offer, perhaps trying to sell medium-value BLUE or GREEN to pick up extra RED. Cat, moving last, will respond after observing two full proposals and may decide whether to act more aggressively to acquire BLUE (which cat privately values most), or to seize any mispriced opportunities involving GREEN. Rejections are relatively likely in this opening round as players feel out the space and avoid being exploited by offers that seem tilted against them.",
