          "responses": {
            "otter-blue-7516": {
              "accepted": false
            },
            "peacock-red-3668": {
              "accepted": true
            }
          }
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "round": 2,
      "round_explanation": "Entering the final round, the remaining opportunities for gain are limited and inventory imbalances are more visible. Cat has accumulated extra BLUE via trades with both otter and peacock, confirming to others that cat values BLUE enough to give up both GREEN and some RED for it. Otter has been the main counterparty in BLUE-for-GREEN trades and has also acquired some additional RED from peacock, reinforcing otter’s strategy of converting BLUE into safer value. Peacock has managed a favorable BLUE-for-RED swap with cat but has otherwise been more cautious, declining some offers and seeing others rejected. Because this is the last round, players can no longer hold out for future gains: a small positive surplus now is better than zero later. At the same time, no one wants to destroy value by trading away RED unless the margin is clear. Proposers in this final sequence therefore tend to present relatively straightforward, mildly generous offers that target their comparative advantages: peacock may seek to offload remaining GREEN for either RED or BLUE; otter may try one last time to trade away excess BLUE for RED; cat, realizing this is the last chance to exploit a high BLUE valuation, might offer GREEN to pull in any remaining BLUE that others are still holding. Final accepted trades in this round tend to be modest, closing off residual gains without radically changing any one player’s portfolio.",
      "turns": [
        {
          "turn_index": 0,
          "sender_id": "peacock-red-3668",
          "buy": {
            "BLUE": 1
          },
          "sell": {
